{"id":"1301.3356","submitter":"Nathanael Berestycki","authors":"Nathanael Berestycki","title":"Diffusion in planar Liouville quantum gravity","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We construct the natural diffusion in the random geometry of planar Liouville\nquantum gravity. Formally, this is the Brownian motion in a domain $D$ of the\ncomplex plane for which the Riemannian metric tensor at a point $z \\in D$ is\ngiven by $\\exp (\\gamma h(z) - \\frac12 \\gamma^2 \\E (h(z)^2))$. Here $h$ is an\ninstance of the Gaussian Free Field on $D$ and $\\gamma \\in (0,2)$ is a\nparameter. We show that the process is almost surely continuous and enjoys\ncertain conformal invariance properties. We also estimate the Hausdorff\ndimension of times that the diffusion spends in the thick points of the\nGaussian Free Field, and show that it spends Lebesgue-almost all its time in\nthe set of $\\gamma$-thick points, almost surely.\n  The diffusion is constructed by a limiting procedure after regularisation of\nthe Gaussian Free Field. The proof is inspired by arguments of\nDuplantier--Sheffield for the convergence of the Liouville quantum gravity\nmeasure, previous work on multifractal random measures, and relies also on\nestimates on the occupation measure of planar Brownian motion by Dembo, Peres,\nRosen and Zeitouni.\n  A similar but deeper result has been independently and simultaneously proved\nby Garban, Rhodes and Vargas.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Jan 2013 14:22:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-01-16"}
